{"id":"1605.02868","submitter":"Souvik Dhara","authors":"Souvik Dhara, Remco van der Hofstad, Johan S.H. van Leeuwaarden and\n  Sanchayan Sen","title":"Critical window for the configuration model: finite third moment degrees","comments":"33 pages. Minor improvements","journal-ref":"Electron.J.Probab. 22 (2017) 1-33","doi":"10.1214/17-EJP29","report-no":null,"categories":"math.PR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We investigate the component sizes of the critical configuration model, as\nwell as the related problem of critical percolation on a supercritical\nconfiguration model. We show that, at criticality, the finite third moment\nassumption on the asymptotic degree distribution is enough to guarantee that\nthe sizes of the largest connected components are of the order $n^{2/3}$ and\nthe re-scaled component sizes (ordered in a decreasing manner) converge to the\nordered excursion lengths of an inhomogeneous Brownian Motion with a parabolic\ndrift. We use percolation to study the evolution of these component sizes while\npassing through the critical window and show that the vector of percolation\ncluster-sizes, considered as a process in the critical window, converge to the\nmultiplicative coalescent process in the sense of finite dimensional\ndistributions. This behavior was first observed for Erd\\H{o}s-R\\'enyi random\ngraphs by Aldous (1997) and our results provide support for the empirical\nevidences that the nature of the phase transition for a wide array of\nrandom-graph models are universal in nature. Further, we show that the\nre-scaled component sizes and surplus edges converge jointly under a strong\ntopology, at each fixed location of the scaling window.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 10 May 2016 06:54:04 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 30 Nov 2016 19:18:03 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 15 Feb 2017 11:02:10 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-02-16"}
